    "body": "This ticket is related to my [\"Short circuit is slower than nested if\"](http://codespeak.net/pipermail/cython-dev/2009-September/006870.html) post. Robert pointed out that it is also a [semantics problem if the called function had side-effects](http://codespeak.net/pipermail/cython-dev/2009-September/006873.html). I felt that semantics errors are more critical, so I am posting this ticket as such.\n\nBelow is code that highlights the problem.\n\n```\n# Filename: app.pyx\ncdef long count\n\ncdef long positive1(long a):  # NOTE: \"cdef long\"\n  global count\n  count += 1\n  return a > 0\n\ncdef positive2(long a):       # NOTE: \"cdef\" only\n  global count\n  count += 1\n  return a > 0\n\ndef test():\n  result = [ n = positive1(0) and 1\n  result.append(count)\n  n = positive2(0) and 1\n  result.append(count)\n  return result\n```\n\n```\n# Filename: main.py\nimport app\nprint app.test()\n```\n\nResult of running \"python main.py\" is [0,2,3](count]\n) when it should be [into app.c generated by Cython:\n```\n/* \"app/app.pyx\":15\n * def test():\n *   result = [count](0,1,2].\n\nLooking)\n *   n = positive1(0) and 1             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<\n *   result.append(count)\n *   n = positive2(0) and 1\n */\n  if (__pyx_f_3app_positive1(0)) {\n    __pyx_t_3 = 1;\n  } else {\n    __pyx_t_3 = __pyx_f_3app_positive1(0);\n  }\n```\n\nAs we can see, positive1() is called twice if it returns false initially.\n\nI observed that when positive1() is declared as \"cdef long\", Cython generates code with the wrong semantics. When positive2() is declared as \"cdef\" only, Cython generates the right semantics.\n\nMigrated from http://trac.cython.org/ticket/404",
